The paper deals with data structures for performing predecessor searches, which is a fundamental problem in data structures and algorithms. The focus is on achieving query times that depend on the distribution of queries, which suggests a connection to information theory (cs.IT) and coding theory (cs.CC). The use of entropy as a measure of query distribution further supports this connection. The paper also discusses the space-time tradeoff, which is a common theme in data structures (cs.DS). The use of weights on universe elements suggests a connection to algorithms for weighted data (cs.AL), and the consideration of unknown distributions suggests a connection to machine learning and statistics (cs.DM).
